title: For Sale/Trade:  Octagonal Barrel 1850’s Percussion Rifle
postcontent: Up for sale in a 1850's era percussion rifle.  I got this from a family member many years ago, and quite frankly, I knew nothing about firearms of this type or era.  I recently paid to have an appraisal done on this rifle, and now that I have the facts, iit's time to sell it.Rifle was graded at 85% condition.  It was said to be 36 caliber.  This rifle would have started life as a flintlock operating rifle, but was converted to percussion operation.  The conversion was something done in the period of the original owner, and it's common to see this on rifles of this era. The barrel is an octagonal barrel with seven sided interior barrel, no rifling.  The barrel in inscribed with the name "Campbell" on the top, and appraiser said this would have been the original owner (not barrel maker or gunsmith who built the rifle).  It's a set trigger and lock trigger operation.  The lockplate and barrel are made of iron.  The stock is American Walnut with a lead tipped forend.  The left side of the buttstock has some embellishment that appraiser said is rare/desirable in this type of rifle...it's something "Campbell" would have ordered as a special at the time he had it made.What it needs...Rear sight is missing.  Appraiser said this is something that can be made or found as new old stock.  The catch pin can that allows the hammer to stay in the cocked position is worn and needs replaced. There are a few cracks in the stock that a new owner may be interested in having repair professionally.The appraised value AS IS was $1900.  If you had stock repaired, fixed trigger catch, and fixed the rear sight, estimated value would be $2500.I'm offering this for sale at $900.  As this is an antique, no FFL is required.  I AM WILLING TO SHIP THIS RIFLE.  Cash talks.  Make an offer. Motivated seller.  I can only post the one picture, but reply to the ad and I will get you multiple pictures and answer any questions.
